title: For Sale:  LGB Trains & Track
postcontent:
PRICE REDUCTION TODAY on this wonderful collection of used and unused Large Scale Trains ready for your Garden Layout or back porch or wherever you can get away with it.  It’s not too early to be planning and testing your Easter Layout.  Carrying the little eggs and candy and chocolate round and round.  Cool.

First there is an LGB Short Island Railroad train set.  Includes the engine, two cars, 12 pieces of curved track, and the transformer.  It’s been run, but not really a whole lot.

Three Playmobil cars new and unused.  Two 4104 gondolas and one 4105 gondola with a load of pipes.

Two Bachman Big Hauler #44 South Pacific Coast Passenger Cars.  Also new and unused.  Sort of.  One car was on the track for a wee bit, but I don’t think it was ever actually placed into service.  There is but one box, and it is not at all pristine.  Far from it.

Finally, there is the track.  
•	Of course there is the original circle with 12 pieces of track.  
•	Ten Aristo-Craft 36” straight track.  Mostly new and unused, but not well cared for.  So it’s dusty and dirty.  But in otherwise great condition.  
•	Fourteen Aristo-Craft curved track new and unused and pristine.
•	Sixteen Aristo-Craft 12” straight track new and unused and pristine.
•	Fourteen Aristo-Craft 12” one-half curved track new and unused and pristine.
•	Two Aristo-Craft left turnouts new and unused and pristine.
•	Two Aristo-Craft right turnouts new and unused and pristine.

There’s a lot of trains here.  Perhaps too much for any one person to absorb.  I suppose the Bachman and/or the Playmobil cars could be sold first, together or separately.  Then the LGB Short Island train set.  Engine, cars, track, transformer.  And then finally the track and turnouts.

I arrived at the price of $800 by staring into the clouds until the moon rose, and then looking into the puddle left by the rain and asking:

“Puddle Puddle on the walk, 
Time for you to hear me talk,
what’s the price 
and tell me twice.”  

At which point my wife said the neighbors thought I was bereft of my senses and had locked their children and pets indoors.

So be it.  If you think, as do I, that this collection of Large Scale Trains is worth more, please feel free to offer more.  It will not embarrass me in the least.  In fact, it will warm my heart to know there are honest buyers left in the world.  Or at least in Arizona.

Purchase with great confidence.  You absolutely will not be disappointed.  You may even be thrilled with your purchase.

Cash is preferred, but interesting trades will be considered.  Leupold, EoTech, or Colt or Smith & Wesson or Sig or…..  Perhaps a Short barrel .357 magnum.  Please no leather, whips, chains, or teenage children.  Already have enough of those.

title: For Sale:  Inron MY803 "Poor Man's Hinderer" Orange EDC Folding Knife NEW
location: Ships anywhere in CONUS, Las Vegas, Nevada
postcontent:
- USA Based Dealer -

NEWLY  ARRIVED 
Inron MY803 Folding EDC Pocket Knife w/Orange G10 Handle
"Poor  Man's  Hinderer"

As a knife enthusiast, you may be "in the know" about the high quality yet low cost Sanrenmu, Enlan, and Ganzo knives. 

These little known knife manufacturers are credited with making some very high quality, well designed yet affordable folder knives especially well suited for every day carry purposes. In fact if you have any contacts within the knife/cutlery trade you will find out that Ganzo, Sanrenmu and Enlan's other activities include manufacturing knives for numerous western brands such as Benchmande, Spyderco, Buck, and SOG. So believe me when I say you're getting a lot for your money with these guys.

Now there's a new name to add to this list of quality folders. Enter Inron Cutlery with there beautifully made model MY803, aka "the poor man's Hinderer" so called for its strikingly similar design to that of the Rick Hinderer XM18. Of course this is comparing apples to very expensive oranges but you still get a similar look and ergonomic feel for the price of an XM18 washer.

The MY803 is a good sized folder at 8.8" in total length with a 3.85" high hollow ground blade. The blade steel is a 9Cr13MoV which is similar to 440C steel (more so than the older 8Cr13Mov is). This is a framelock knife with "flipper" action as well as ambidextrous thumb studs. 

I would say the MY803 has an excellent fit and finish for the price. Good detent, very solid lock up without any blade play. It has a flat head pivot screw for easy adjustments and it's ergonomic, oversized handle (easily used with a gloved hand) is made from G10 and is available in 3 color options. 

This solid knife weighs in at 5.6oz using drilled steel liners for weight reduction. For a larger EDC knife, the very slim profile design carries surprisingly well in the pocket. It comes tip up and right hand carry only.


Knife Specs:

Blade Length: 3.9" 
Cutting Edge: 3.5
Blade Thickness: 3.6mm
Blade Steel: 9Cr13MoV Stainless Steel Hollow Ground (59-60HRC)
Open Length: 8.8"
Closed Length: 5"
Weight: 5.6oz  
Handle: Orange G-10/Steel w/Spine Jimping
Handle Thickness: 10.5mm
Lock: Frame Lock
Opening Mechanism: Flipper with Ambidextrous Thumb Studs
Carry: Right Hand Tip Up w/Lanyard Hole
